WEBVTT

00:04.933 --> 00:06.642
GATES:
I'm Henry Louis Gates, Jr.

00:06.666 --> 00:09.309
Welcome to
"Finding Your Roots."

00:09.333 --> 00:12.942
In this episode, we'll
meet actors Pamela Adlon

00:12.966 --> 00:15.076
and Kathryn Hahn.

00:15.100 --> 00:17.909
Two women whose family
trees have been obscured

00:17.933 --> 00:19.533
by family secrets.

00:20.133 --> 00:22.609
HAHN: They went to
a new world and

00:22.633 --> 00:25.166
they shut a door completely.

00:25.700 --> 00:28.166
ADLON: What?!?
How do you know that?

00:28.866 --> 00:32.766
GATES: To uncover their roots,
we've used every tool available.

00:33.300 --> 00:35.876
Genealogists combed through
paper trails stretching back

00:35.900 --> 00:40.009
hundreds of years, while DNA
experts utilized the latest

00:40.033 --> 00:43.542
advances in genetic analysis
to reveal secrets that have

00:43.566 --> 00:46.133
lain hidden for generations.

00:46.366 --> 00:48.076
ADLON: Plot twist!

00:48.100 --> 00:50.809
GATES: And we've compiled
it all into a book of life.

00:50.833 --> 00:51.842
HAHN: Oh wow!

00:51.866 --> 00:53.076
(gasps)

00:53.100 --> 00:54.642
GATES: A record of all
of our discoveries.

00:54.666 --> 00:56.342
You are the
product of this scandal.

00:56.366 --> 00:57.210
HAHN: I know.

00:57.234 --> 00:58.309
GATES: You are the end result.

00:58.333 --> 00:59.676
HAHN: Isn't that nuts?

00:59.700 --> 01:01.609
ADLON: It's the most
exciting thing in the world.

01:01.633 --> 01:03.476
This is an amazing gift.

01:03.500 --> 01:06.309
HAHN: What a freaking story!

01:06.333 --> 01:09.542
GATES: My two guests are tied
together by a common thread:

01:09.566 --> 01:12.742
both descend from people
who concealed the most basic

01:12.766 --> 01:16.309
details about themselves,
leaving their descendants to

01:16.333 --> 01:19.433
wonder who they really are.

01:19.633 --> 01:23.109
In this episode, we'll
separate fact from fiction,

01:23.133 --> 01:26.909
introducing Kathryn and Pamela
to ancestors whose names and

01:26.933 --> 01:30.742
stories had been
hidden for generations,

01:30.766 --> 01:33.666
forever altering how
they see themselves.

01:44.600 --> 01:51.533
(theme music plays)

02:02.766 --> 02:08.900
♪ ♪

02:14.633 --> 02:18.333
GATES: Pamela Adlon is
at the top of her game.

02:18.633 --> 02:20.776
After years in the
show business wilderness,

02:20.800 --> 02:25.142
she's the writer, director and
star of one of television's

02:25.166 --> 02:27.000
most celebrated shows:

02:28.166 --> 02:31.066
the Peabody-award-winning
"Better Things".

02:31.900 --> 02:35.076
But to appreciate just
how far Pamela's come,

02:35.100 --> 02:37.933
you need to go back
to where she started.

02:39.000 --> 02:41.276
Pamela was born
in New York City,

02:41.300 --> 02:44.309
where her mother, an
English expatriate,

02:44.333 --> 02:47.209
struggled to fit in
and where her father,

02:47.233 --> 02:50.609
a Bostonian,
struggled to make a living,

02:50.633 --> 02:52.276
bouncing from job to job

02:52.300 --> 02:55.100
as a writer and
television producer.

02:55.500 --> 02:59.466
Watching her dad work, Pamela
picked up a taste for acting,

03:00.200 --> 03:03.400
and found an agent when
she was just 11 years old,

03:03.766 --> 03:06.233
in a story that sounds
straight out of Hollywood.

03:07.933 --> 03:12.776
ADLON: I met a girl, and she
was saying I have an agent,

03:12.800 --> 03:14.842
and I was like what's that?

03:14.866 --> 03:18.309
And she showed me her
composite picture with like,

03:18.333 --> 03:22.476
her like you know, eating an
apple and throwing a baseball

03:22.500 --> 03:25.842
and it said
Beverly Hecht Agency on it.

03:25.866 --> 03:27.176
GATES: Huh.

03:27.200 --> 03:29.276
ADLON: And so then I went home
and I looked in the phonebook

03:29.300 --> 03:32.376
and I called her and I
made an appointment.

03:32.400 --> 03:34.309
And I sat my parents
down and I was like,

03:34.333 --> 03:37.142
yo, I want to get an
agent and whatever.

03:37.166 --> 03:39.942
And they didn't fight me.

03:39.966 --> 03:41.509
So, we went in to meet her.

03:41.533 --> 03:45.242
She had me read copy
of a tide commercial,

03:45.266 --> 03:48.076
and it was, like, totally
like one of those old movies.

03:48.100 --> 03:50.142
She brings my mother in.

03:50.166 --> 03:51.442
It's like she's got a cigarette.

03:51.466 --> 03:55.600
The kid's terrific.
She's a natural.

03:56.566 --> 03:58.776
GATES: Pamela was,
indeed, a natural.

03:58.800 --> 04:01.509
By the time she was 20,

04:01.533 --> 04:04.176
she'd appeared in a
series of hit sitcoms,

04:04.200 --> 04:05.642
JO: Oh, well look who's here.

04:05.666 --> 04:07.109
GATES: And was
essentially supporting

04:07.133 --> 04:08.542
her parents financially.

04:08.566 --> 04:09.966
ADLON: Not bad, huh?

04:10.200 --> 04:12.809
GATES: Then the
roles stopped coming,

04:12.833 --> 04:15.476
and Pamela went
through a long dry period,

04:15.500 --> 04:17.576
earning money as a voice actor,

04:17.600 --> 04:21.042
and wrestling with a host of
personal challenges:

04:21.066 --> 04:25.009
from the death of her father
to a divorce which left her

04:25.033 --> 04:28.233
the single mother of
three young girls.

04:28.966 --> 04:32.509
Miraculously, she not
only managed to recover,

04:32.533 --> 04:36.233
she turned her ordeal into art.

04:37.000 --> 04:39.876
"Better Things", is a
brilliantly stylized riff on

04:39.900 --> 04:44.076
her own experiences, a fact
that makes Pamela all the more

04:44.100 --> 04:46.866
grateful for its success.

04:48.500 --> 04:52.109
ADLON: I finally took
the bones of my life.

04:52.133 --> 04:55.809
My show is about single
mom, three daughters,

04:55.833 --> 04:57.976
English mother lives next door.

04:58.000 --> 04:59.242
GATES: Mmm-hmm..

04:59.266 --> 05:03.009
ADLON: And what people have
responded to is that they're

05:03.033 --> 05:07.309
passionate about the show and
the content but it's the story

05:07.333 --> 05:12.176
of this lady who made it at 50.

05:12.200 --> 05:14.500
How crazy is that?

05:14.766 --> 05:16.009
GATES: How crazy is that.

05:16.033 --> 05:18.942
ADLON: I should be in the
dust bin at the Jewish Council

05:18.966 --> 05:21.276
Thrift Store in
Sherman Oaks, California.

05:21.300 --> 05:27.566
Like, that all of a
sudden at 50 I become a boss,

05:27.933 --> 05:30.909
a director,
producer, show-runner,

05:30.933 --> 05:33.642
star of my own show.

05:33.666 --> 05:36.633
It's absolutely incredible.

05:37.966 --> 05:40.676
GATES: Ironically, while
"Better Things" explores some

05:40.700 --> 05:45.076
dark territory, particularly
between Pamela's character and

05:45.100 --> 05:46.309
her mother's...

05:46.333 --> 05:48.309
ADLON: Get out.
MOTHER: Don't be ridiculous.

05:48.333 --> 05:50.533
GIRLS: Mom!

05:50.733 --> 05:52.976
ADLON: Get out!

05:53.000 --> 05:55.476
GATES: Making the show
has actually brought the two

05:55.500 --> 05:58.533
closer together in real life.

05:59.566 --> 06:02.942
ADLON: My mother used to drive
me crazy and she would tell me

06:02.966 --> 06:06.733
these stories and I would
be like oh, god, really.

06:07.333 --> 06:10.342
Do I need to hear
about Verizon or like

06:10.366 --> 06:12.876
going to the store?

06:12.900 --> 06:18.700
So one day, I stopped being
driven crazy by my mom and

06:19.000 --> 06:22.209
I just looked at her
and I went, oh, she's funny.

06:22.233 --> 06:25.542
This is funny.
Let me embrace this.

06:25.566 --> 06:28.609
And now my mom is
like my biggest muse.

06:28.633 --> 06:33.809
And she got really extra sassy
with me in the past few years

06:33.833 --> 06:36.376
and her answer is, oh,
you love it because it's

06:36.400 --> 06:39.266
material for your show.

06:40.933 --> 06:43.242
GATES: Much like Pamela,
my second guest,

06:43.266 --> 06:47.276
Kathryn Hahn, has spent
almost her entire life

06:47.300 --> 06:48.666
in show business.

06:49.333 --> 06:52.542
But the beloved actor, who
became a breakout star by

06:52.566 --> 06:55.700
stealing scene after
scene in "Wanda Vision",

06:56.733 --> 06:59.600
didn't start off big, marching
into an agent's office.

07:00.700 --> 07:02.642
Quite the contrary.

07:02.666 --> 07:05.142
Growing up in a
suburb of Cleveland,

07:05.166 --> 07:08.933
Kathryn got her first acting job
when she was in fourth grade,

07:09.200 --> 07:10.776
on "Hickory Hideout,"

07:10.800 --> 07:14.400
a children's program produced
by a local news station.

07:14.866 --> 07:17.700
It wasn't exactly a plumb role,

07:17.933 --> 07:19.909
but Kathryn was hooked.

07:19.933 --> 07:22.900
HAHN: Wow, to be a movie star.

07:23.133 --> 07:26.942
It involved a tree house
and two squirrel puppets,

07:26.966 --> 07:30.976
Nutso and Shirley Squirrely,
and, uh, an owl puppet

07:31.000 --> 07:32.342
called know-it-owl.

07:32.366 --> 07:33.376
GATES: Mm-hmm.

07:33.400 --> 07:35.476
HAHN: And I played a
character named Jenny,

07:35.500 --> 07:38.209
and it would involve
me asking know-it-Owl,

07:38.233 --> 07:40.509
uh, various questions
about getting braces,

07:40.533 --> 07:43.242
or, you know, my
parents got a divorce,

07:43.266 --> 07:46.276
in the show, and I would ask
the owl for advice about

07:46.300 --> 07:47.676
how to deal with it.

07:47.700 --> 07:49.009
It was local
television, you know?

07:49.033 --> 07:50.309
12 people saw it.

07:50.333 --> 07:52.676
It was on at like 6:00, 6:30
in the morning on Saturdays in

07:52.700 --> 07:54.042
Cleveland and Pittsburgh.

07:54.066 --> 07:55.800
GATES: Right.

07:56.333 --> 07:59.009
HAHN: But to me,
I was very excited.

07:59.033 --> 08:01.709
I took it as seriously
as if I, as if,

08:01.733 --> 08:04.842
that I, you know, I was
in "The Deer Hunter".

08:04.866 --> 08:07.266
Like I was so serious about it.

08:08.433 --> 08:11.842
GATES: Perhaps unsurprisingly,
"Hickory Hideout" didn't lead

08:11.866 --> 08:13.842
to bigger roles.

08:13.866 --> 08:17.609
Nevertheless, Kathryn
was determined to act,

08:17.633 --> 08:20.809
and her parents
supported her ambitions.

08:20.833 --> 08:24.100
For years, that seemed
like a foolish choice.

08:26.066 --> 08:29.509
After college, Kathryn
moved to New York City and

08:29.533 --> 08:32.533
was forced to confront the
reality of her profession,

08:33.300 --> 08:36.076
working in
restaurants and hair salons,

08:36.100 --> 08:38.900
as she chased jobs
that never came.

08:39.333 --> 08:42.209
HAHN: Those 20s were
a bl, a mad blur of

08:42.233 --> 08:44.509
racing towards auditions
and not getting them

08:44.533 --> 08:46.342
and handing out head shots.

08:46.366 --> 08:47.776
GATES: Yeah.

08:47.800 --> 08:49.242
HAHN: Trying to get an agent.

08:49.266 --> 08:50.609
I mean, I would
write on my head shot,

08:50.633 --> 08:54.409
"You've got to see this girl!"
and I'm like, "Just fake it!"

08:54.433 --> 08:56.409
And, like, not
getting any calls.

08:56.433 --> 08:57.410
It was awful.

08:57.434 --> 08:59.776
GATES: So what,
what kept you going?

08:59.800 --> 09:02.309
HAHN: There was no choice.
I had no choice.

09:02.333 --> 09:03.709
There was no other option.

09:03.733 --> 09:05.009
GATES: Right. None.

09:05.033 --> 09:06.276
HAHN: None.

09:06.300 --> 09:07.642
GATES: But did deep down you
think I'm going to make it?

09:07.666 --> 09:08.676
HAHN: Yes!

09:08.700 --> 09:10.009
I didn't think I was
going to, didn't know.

09:10.033 --> 09:11.942
Again, I didn't know if
I was ever going to land

09:11.966 --> 09:13.942
somewhere successfully.

09:13.966 --> 09:15.842
I didn't know how it
was going to look,

09:15.866 --> 09:17.933
but I had no option.

09:19.166 --> 09:22.066
GATES: Kathryn's "options"
would take time to appear,

09:22.733 --> 09:25.533
but once they did,
they came in bunches.

09:26.300 --> 09:29.742
Starting out with small
parts in big budget comedies,

09:29.766 --> 09:32.466
she slowly moved into
prestige television,

09:32.766 --> 09:34.276
and became a star.

09:34.300 --> 09:36.800
Creating a string of
indelible characters.

09:37.033 --> 09:39.209
HAHN: The name's
Agatha Harkness.

09:39.233 --> 09:41.966
Lovely to
finally meet you, dear.

09:42.166 --> 09:44.742
GATES: And now, at an age
when Hollywood historically

09:44.766 --> 09:47.509
provides fewer
starring roles for women,

09:47.533 --> 09:49.333
Kathryn is a phenomenon.

09:50.633 --> 09:52.766
It's been an incredible journey.

09:53.433 --> 09:56.342
But when she looks back for
the source of her success,

09:56.366 --> 10:00.009
Kathryn returns to the people
who were there all along:

10:00.033 --> 10:01.933
her parents.

10:03.133 --> 10:07.609
HAHN: Both of them
believed in me and my,

10:07.633 --> 10:11.876
this bananas dream to be an
actor without a question from

10:11.900 --> 10:13.109
the beginning.

10:13.133 --> 10:14.309
GATES: Wow.

10:14.333 --> 10:18.809
HAHN: And that support I think
was clearly imperative

10:18.833 --> 10:21.109
to where I am.

10:21.133 --> 10:22.209
GATES: Crucial.

10:22.233 --> 10:23.376
HAHN: Crucial.

10:23.400 --> 10:24.809
GATES: Crucial, but what's
wrong with your parents?

10:24.833 --> 10:26.742
Normal parents would say,
"Are you crazy?"

10:26.766 --> 10:27.543
You know like...

10:27.567 --> 10:28.642
HAHN: Yeah, they just didn't.

10:28.666 --> 10:30.109
I mean, I was just all
of a sudden in a U-Haul

10:30.133 --> 10:31.010
going to New York.

10:31.034 --> 10:32.042
GATES: Yeah.

10:32.066 --> 10:33.209
HAHN: And they
were like, "okay."

10:33.233 --> 10:34.276
GATES: That's amazing.

10:34.300 --> 10:35.509
HAHN: They just
didn't have any...

10:35.533 --> 10:37.176
There was no question that
it was just going to happen.

10:37.200 --> 10:39.276
GATES: And never once from
the time you were a little kid

10:39.300 --> 10:41.342
when you first
voiced this fantasy,

10:41.366 --> 10:43.776
never once did they say,
"Baby, it's a hard way..."

10:43.800 --> 10:44.777
HAHN: Never.

10:44.801 --> 10:46.509
GATES: Or, "You got to eat,"
or you know?

10:46.533 --> 10:47.776
"You'd make a lot
more money as a lawyer?"

10:47.800 --> 10:48.909
HAHN: Never.
GATES: Never.

10:48.933 --> 10:50.942
HAHN: I mean, it was
just an unquestioned thing.

10:50.966 --> 10:51.976
GATES: You were lucky.

10:52.000 --> 10:53.242
HAHN: I was so lucky.

10:53.266 --> 10:54.576
GATES: Yeah.
No, you were.

10:54.600 --> 10:56.433
HAHN: I agree with you.

10:56.633 --> 10:59.042
GATES: My guests both come
from tight-knit families that

10:59.066 --> 11:01.276
nurtured their dreams.

11:01.300 --> 11:04.509
Those same families
also harbored secrets that

11:04.533 --> 11:07.433
shrouded their roots in mystery.

11:07.800 --> 11:11.000
It was time to bring
these secrets to light.

11:11.633 --> 11:14.409
I started with Pamela, who
came to me with a very

11:14.433 --> 11:17.842
basic question: she wanted
to know the identity of

11:17.866 --> 11:19.933
her mother's father.

11:20.433 --> 11:22.942
She'd heard rumors that the
man whom she believed to be

11:22.966 --> 11:27.233
her grandfather wasn't in
fact related to her at all,

11:28.600 --> 11:32.166
and that her mother was
the product of an affair.

11:32.866 --> 11:35.876
But Pamela didn't know if
these rumors were true.

11:35.900 --> 11:37.309
And her mother's family,

11:37.333 --> 11:39.876
with its very English
sense of propriety,

11:39.900 --> 11:42.566
wasn't about
to help her find out.

11:43.333 --> 11:47.142
ADLON: It's it's very hard,
the English side,

11:47.166 --> 11:50.776
because there are
things you don't do.

11:50.800 --> 11:54.176
And so, um, when one generation

11:54.200 --> 11:57.400
does not reveal

11:57.700 --> 12:01.909
certain things then the next
generation feels that they're

12:01.933 --> 12:03.242
not to be revealed.

12:03.266 --> 12:04.509
GATES: Yes.

12:04.533 --> 12:07.176
ADLON: If they have gone to
their graves without talking

12:07.200 --> 12:09.076
about it, it's not
anybody's business...

12:09.100 --> 12:10.276
GATES: Right.

12:10.300 --> 12:12.076
ADLON: And that's
frustrating for me.

12:12.100 --> 12:13.876
GATES: It's the
generational cone of silence.

12:13.900 --> 12:15.142
ADLON: Yeah, man.

12:15.166 --> 12:21.076
I want to know and I don't
want to disrespect my lineage,

12:21.100 --> 12:25.666
but I really, I'm so curious.

12:27.233 --> 12:30.076
GATES: Pamela's
curiosity was palpable,

12:30.100 --> 12:33.766
but satisfying it would
test our team to the limit.

12:35.000 --> 12:37.876
Her mother, Marina Lucy Leece,

12:37.900 --> 12:41.566
was born in
Birkenhead, England in 1935.

12:42.266 --> 12:44.076
According to her
birth certificate,

12:44.100 --> 12:47.433
her parents were
Leonard and Phyllis Leece.

12:47.633 --> 12:51.409
And there were no documents to
suggest that Leonard was not

12:51.433 --> 12:55.333
Marina's father, but that's
exactly what Marina believed.

12:56.400 --> 13:00.433
This left us with
only one option: DNA.

13:02.700 --> 13:06.442
We compared Marina's DNA to
that of millions of others in

13:06.466 --> 13:10.476
publicly-available databases,
and we found that she has

13:10.500 --> 13:15.633
roughly 250 matches within
the last five generations.

13:16.266 --> 13:18.842
But when we started looking
among them for matches that

13:18.866 --> 13:21.242
connect her to Leonard Leece,

13:21.266 --> 13:23.166
we got a very a
different number.

13:24.433 --> 13:26.809
ADLON: I see the word zero.

13:26.833 --> 13:27.743
Zero!

13:27.767 --> 13:29.842
GATES: So, you
know what that means?

13:29.866 --> 13:32.342
It means that your
mother was absolutely right.

13:32.366 --> 13:37.076
She has absolutely no genetic
relationship to Leonard Leece.

13:37.100 --> 13:40.642
She is not his
biological daughter.

13:40.666 --> 13:42.209
ADLON: Damn.

13:42.233 --> 13:44.142
GATES: So, that's the first
thing we had to establish.

13:44.166 --> 13:45.276
ADLON: Copy.

13:45.300 --> 13:47.609
GATES: Was this story true?

13:47.633 --> 13:48.642
ADLON: Wow.

13:48.666 --> 13:50.409
GATES: And it's true.

13:50.433 --> 13:53.542
So, this is where
things get a little tricky.

13:53.566 --> 13:55.933
ADLON: Who is this interloper?

13:56.600 --> 14:00.309
GATES: DNA was clearly telling
us that Leonard was not your

14:00.333 --> 14:03.509
biological grandfather but it
wasn't telling us who was your

14:03.533 --> 14:04.709
biological grandfather.

14:04.733 --> 14:06.142
ADLON: Mm-hum.

14:06.166 --> 14:08.342
GATES: Part of the problem
is that DNA testing just

14:08.366 --> 14:11.009
isn't as popular, and this
will not shock you,

14:11.033 --> 14:14.176
or as mainstream in the
united kingdom as it is

14:14.200 --> 14:17.433
here in the United States.

14:17.866 --> 14:19.542
For reasons that we
have discussed already.

14:19.566 --> 14:20.842
ADLON: Oh my god.

14:20.866 --> 14:22.542
GATES: That is a secret that
we are not going to discuss...

14:22.566 --> 14:23.576
ADLON: Yes.

14:23.600 --> 14:24.609
GATES: And it will be
taken to the grave.

14:24.633 --> 14:27.200
ADLON: Totally.

14:27.500 --> 14:29.842
GATES: Lacking
enough DNA samples,

14:29.866 --> 14:31.942
the next phase of our
research would consume

14:31.966 --> 14:34.276
almost five years,

14:34.300 --> 14:37.733
more time than we've ever
spent on a guest before.

14:38.166 --> 14:40.076
But it was worth it.

14:40.100 --> 14:43.809
Eventually, we were able
to tie Pamela's mother Marina

14:43.833 --> 14:47.933
to a married couple named
Benjamin and Rose Walthew.

14:48.733 --> 14:50.409
Benjamin and Rose lived
