28:29.500 --> 28:32.476
GATES: Kathryn wondered
whether Wilhelm ever regretted

28:32.500 --> 28:35.566
leaving his wife and
children behind in Germany.

28:36.166 --> 28:38.042
There's no way to
know for certain,

28:38.066 --> 28:42.209
but his obituary, which
celebrates his life in detail,

28:42.233 --> 28:44.566
contains a telling clue.

28:45.400 --> 28:48.409
HAHN: "He was esteemed
for his stern integrity,

28:48.433 --> 28:50.776
his shrewd business methods,

28:50.800 --> 28:53.109
as a pleasant companion
and true friend."

28:53.133 --> 28:54.742
Hmm.

28:54.766 --> 28:56.642
"Thus, in the course of nature,

28:56.666 --> 28:59.676
has a well-rounded
life reached its close",

28:59.700 --> 29:03.009
wow, "And the loved and
loving husband and father

29:03.033 --> 29:06.109
has gone to his last
and long repose."

29:06.133 --> 29:09.242
GATES: That is the obituary of
your third-great-grandfather,

29:09.266 --> 29:10.876
Wilhelm.

29:10.900 --> 29:14.209
He died on February 21st,
1900, in Wisconsin.

29:14.233 --> 29:16.109
And there is
absolutely no mention...

29:16.133 --> 29:17.043
HAHN: No mention.

29:17.067 --> 29:18.376
GATES: Of that
family he left behind.

29:18.400 --> 29:21.109
HAHN: It sounds like
they chose to just,

29:21.133 --> 29:25.166
they went to a new world...

29:25.500 --> 29:26.443
GATES: Right.

29:26.467 --> 29:28.576
HAHN: And they shut
a door completely.

29:28.600 --> 29:29.709
GATES: Big time.

29:29.733 --> 29:33.642
They shut a vault of
memories and associations

29:33.666 --> 29:35.842
and responsibilities.

29:35.866 --> 29:39.009
Your third-great-grandparents
came to the United States and

29:39.033 --> 29:40.676
totally reinvented themselves.

29:40.700 --> 29:41.742
HAHN: Yup.

29:41.766 --> 29:42.976
GATES: That's the bottom line.

29:43.000 --> 29:44.442
All immigrants
reinvent themselves.

29:44.466 --> 29:45.509
HAHN: But this...

29:45.533 --> 29:47.633
GATES: But they really
reinvented themselves.

29:48.066 --> 29:51.609
Do you think they kept all of
this a secret from everyone?

29:51.633 --> 29:53.642
I mean, this is
a lot of secret to keep.

29:53.666 --> 29:56.209
HAHN: Yeah. I think so.

29:56.233 --> 29:58.409
But, like, what a thing
to take to the grave.

29:58.433 --> 29:59.842
GATES: Yeah.

29:59.866 --> 30:05.566
HAHN: I mean, what a thing,
to take to the grave.

30:05.966 --> 30:07.842
GATES: But on the other hand,
he followed his heart.

30:07.866 --> 30:08.643
He fell in love.

30:08.667 --> 30:09.742
HAHN: Yeah.

30:09.766 --> 30:10.776
GATES: And you're here.

30:10.800 --> 30:12.109
HAHN: Yes, exactly!

30:12.133 --> 30:13.476
GATES: I mean...

30:13.500 --> 30:16.209
HAHN: The fact that that had to
happen for this to happen, is.

30:16.233 --> 30:17.942
GATES: Yeah. You are the
product of this scandal.

30:17.966 --> 30:18.777
HAHN: I know.

30:18.801 --> 30:19.842
GATES: You are the end result.

30:19.866 --> 30:21.833
HAHN: Isn't that nuts?

30:22.433 --> 30:25.876
GATES: We'd already introduced
Pamela Adlon to her biological

30:25.900 --> 30:30.776
grandfather, uncovering a
host of secrets in the small

30:30.800 --> 30:33.876
English city where
her mother grew up.

30:33.900 --> 30:36.976
Now, turning to
Pamela's paternal roots,

30:37.000 --> 30:40.242
we found ourselves in a
very different place,

30:40.266 --> 30:44.566
confronting secrets of
a very different nature.

30:44.800 --> 30:49.076
Pamela's father descends
from eastern European Jews,

30:49.100 --> 30:51.876
and Pamela told me that while
she felt connected to her

30:51.900 --> 30:55.276
Jewish ancestors, the family
never spoke about their past,

30:55.300 --> 30:59.600
so she knows almost
nothing about their lives.

31:00.900 --> 31:04.833
We set out to change that,
starting with the 1910 census

31:05.300 --> 31:08.100
for the town of
Medford, Massachusetts,

31:08.400 --> 31:11.833
where Pamela's grandfather,
Harry Segall, was raised.

31:14.166 --> 31:15.442
ADLON: Man.

31:15.466 --> 31:18.609
"Frank Segall,
head of the family.

31:18.633 --> 31:21.233
Age, 46.
Place of birth, Russia.

31:22.100 --> 31:24.176
Native language, Yiddish."

31:24.200 --> 31:25.143
GATES: Mmm-hmm.

31:25.167 --> 31:28.100
ADLON: "Occupation, janitor."
Respect.

31:28.700 --> 31:34.466
Fanny, awe, his wife, age 36.
Place of birth, Russia.

31:35.500 --> 31:39.033
Native language, Yiddish.
Love that.

31:39.733 --> 31:42.176
Year of immigration 1895.

31:42.200 --> 31:46.776
Dora, daughter, age 12.
Place of birth, Massachusetts.

31:46.800 --> 31:48.709
Harry, son, age nine.

31:48.733 --> 31:50.609
Place of birth,
Massachusetts."

31:50.633 --> 31:52.542
GATES: That is your
grandfather Harry when he was

31:52.566 --> 31:55.876
nine years old listed in the
household of his parents in

31:55.900 --> 31:58.376
the federal census and
his parents are your

31:58.400 --> 32:01.076
great-grandparents,
Frank and Fanny Segall.

32:01.100 --> 32:02.109
ADLON: Wow!

32:02.133 --> 32:03.509
GATES: Have you heard
of Frank and Fanny?

32:03.533 --> 32:04.542
ADLON: No.

32:04.566 --> 32:05.510
GATES: Really?

32:05.534 --> 32:08.009
ADLON: I mean Frank
is a family name.

32:08.033 --> 32:10.609
GATES: But if I said
what are the names of

32:10.633 --> 32:11.343
your great-grandparents?

32:11.367 --> 32:12.476
ADLON: Oh, no.

32:12.500 --> 32:14.142
GATES: Well, you just met
your great-grandparents.

32:14.166 --> 32:16.700
ADLON: That's incredible.

32:17.533 --> 32:20.542
GATES: This census indicates
that Frank Segall was born in

32:20.566 --> 32:24.300
Russia sometime around 1864.

32:24.966 --> 32:27.042
From a genealogical perspective,

32:27.066 --> 32:30.276
this information
wasn't terribly useful.

32:30.300 --> 32:33.209
Russia, at the time,
was a huge empire,

32:33.233 --> 32:36.642
and no other documents named
Frank's birthplace with any

32:36.666 --> 32:39.109
greater specificity.

32:39.133 --> 32:41.876
It seemed like we'd
hit a brick wall.

32:41.900 --> 32:44.842
But then, expanding our search,

32:44.866 --> 32:48.542
we uncovered a U.S. Army
draft registration card

32:48.566 --> 32:51.242
for Frank's younger
brother Samuel.

32:51.266 --> 32:54.876
It indicated that Samuel was
born in a town called Gritsev,

32:54.900 --> 32:58.333
and, suddenly, that
brick wall collapsed,

32:59.733 --> 33:02.609
can you see in what modern-day
country the town is?

33:02.633 --> 33:03.709
ADLON: Ukraine.

33:03.733 --> 33:04.876
GATES: Ukraine.

33:04.900 --> 33:06.942
Frank came from the area
of the Russian empire

33:06.966 --> 33:08.076
that's now Ukraine.

33:08.100 --> 33:09.176
ADLON: Wow.

33:09.200 --> 33:10.509
GATES: Have you
ever been to Ukraine?

33:10.533 --> 33:11.477
ADLON: No.

33:11.501 --> 33:13.776
GATES: No. Well,
please turn the page.

33:13.800 --> 33:19.033
ADLON: Wow.
Belarus. I had...

33:19.366 --> 33:22.076
A guy came to fix
my dishwasher once.

33:22.100 --> 33:25.366
He was from Belarus.
He was a scary man.

33:26.900 --> 33:30.209
GATES: Pamela, you're looking
at a photo of a gravestone

33:30.233 --> 33:33.309
taken around 1912,
likely in Gritsev,

33:33.333 --> 33:35.842
would you please read
the translated section of

33:35.866 --> 33:38.276
the Hebrew
inscription on the stone?

33:38.300 --> 33:39.809
ADLON: Okay. Good.

33:39.833 --> 33:42.642
I was having PTSD of Hebrew
school and I thought you were

33:42.666 --> 33:45.500
going to make me read
the Hebrew on the stone.

33:46.100 --> 33:49.176
"Here is buried a
pure and honest man.

33:49.200 --> 33:55.133
He was famous rabbi
Yitzhak son of Tzvi Halevy."

33:55.666 --> 33:58.542
GATES: Yitzhak was the father
of your great-grandfather

33:58.566 --> 34:00.142
Frank Segall.

34:00.166 --> 34:03.642
You're looking at your great-
great-grandfather's gravestone.

34:03.666 --> 34:04.742
ADLON: And he was a rabbi.

34:04.766 --> 34:06.576
GATES: He was a rabbi, dear.
You just read it.

34:06.600 --> 34:09.433
ADLON: Yes.
Oh, my god.

34:10.933 --> 34:12.309
GATES: Were you bat mizvahed?

34:12.333 --> 34:16.842
ADLON: I mean the amount
of time I spent in temple.

34:16.866 --> 34:21.209
If somebody had just
said to me your great,

34:21.233 --> 34:22.342
my great-great?

34:22.366 --> 34:23.709
GATES:
Great-great-grandfather.

34:23.733 --> 34:25.942
ADLON: Was a rabbi I
would have been like,

34:25.966 --> 34:30.542
oh, wait, let me catch up
to this sermon right now.

34:30.566 --> 34:32.466
It's mind-blowing.

34:34.200 --> 34:36.309
GATES: This photo was likely
taken around the time of

34:36.333 --> 34:39.433
Yitzhak's death in 1912.

34:39.800 --> 34:41.742
The women in it
are his daughters,

34:41.766 --> 34:43.800
Zhenya and Menikha.

34:44.600 --> 34:46.009
They are the younger sisters

34:46.033 --> 34:48.509
of Pamela's
great-grandfather, Frank.

34:48.533 --> 34:51.133
And thus Pamela's
great-grand aunts.

34:53.066 --> 34:54.809
ADLON: Oh, my god.

34:54.833 --> 34:56.409
GATES: See any
family resemblances?

34:56.433 --> 34:58.142
ADLON: They're so beautiful.

34:58.166 --> 35:01.909
No. I mean they almost
look like Italian.

35:01.933 --> 35:04.133
GATES: Or maybe Russian.

35:04.966 --> 35:07.342
(laughter)

35:07.366 --> 35:08.509
Maybe Ukrainian.

35:08.533 --> 35:11.642
ADLON: Oh, wait.
Oh, wait.

35:11.666 --> 35:13.966
Um, yes, that's what I meant.

35:16.833 --> 35:20.733
GATES: Pamela had never heard
of either Zhenya or Menikha,

35:21.366 --> 35:23.966
and we soon uncovered
the likely reason why.

35:24.833 --> 35:28.342
Unlike Frank and three
of their other siblings,

35:28.366 --> 35:31.900
neither of the sisters
chose to immigrate to America.

35:32.266 --> 35:35.666
And that decision
would cost them dearly.

35:36.066 --> 35:39.800
In 1941, Nazi
Germany invaded Ukraine,

35:40.666 --> 35:43.676
which was then part
of the Soviet Union,

35:43.700 --> 35:46.700
and began to exterminate
its Jewish population.

35:47.866 --> 35:50.642
We don't know what
happened to Zhenya,

35:50.666 --> 35:54.109
but her sister Menikha was
evacuated to the interior of

35:54.133 --> 35:58.142
Russia because her
husband, a technician,

35:58.166 --> 36:01.709
and two of her daughters, were
considered to be essential to

36:01.733 --> 36:04.366
the soviet war effort.

36:04.633 --> 36:08.642
One of her daughters, however,
a woman named Clara Birman,

36:08.666 --> 36:10.900
chose to stay behind.

36:11.500 --> 36:13.976
GATES: Her name is nowhere
on the list of those

36:14.000 --> 36:15.309
who were evacuated.

36:15.333 --> 36:16.676
ADLON: Oh.

36:16.700 --> 36:18.876
GATES: So, we wanted to
find out what happened to her.

36:18.900 --> 36:19.843
ADLON: Yeah.

36:19.867 --> 36:21.442
GATES: We feared
for the worst, of course.

36:21.466 --> 36:23.076
Could you please turn the page?

36:23.100 --> 36:25.709
Pamela, that photograph
was taken just before the

36:25.733 --> 36:28.600
German invasion of the
Soviet Union in 1941.

36:28.933 --> 36:32.276
It shows Clara Birman
with her Ukrainian husband,

36:32.300 --> 36:35.576
Anatoly and their two
young children: Vladimir,

36:35.600 --> 36:40.266
born in 1940, and
Lyudmila, born in 1938.

36:40.966 --> 36:42.342
ADLON: Oh, my god.

36:42.366 --> 36:43.509
GATES: Did you ever hear
of any of these people?

36:43.533 --> 36:45.076
ADLON: Never.

36:45.100 --> 36:47.409
GATES: Well, upon the German
invasion of the Soviet Union,

36:47.433 --> 36:51.709
Clara's husband, Anatoly was
activated for military duty

36:51.733 --> 36:54.042
and before he reported he took
Clara and the children to stay

36:54.066 --> 36:57.509
with his mother in one of the
ethnically Ukrainian villages

36:57.533 --> 36:59.476
outside of Kiev.

36:59.500 --> 37:04.300
No one but Anatoly's mother
knew that Clara was Jewish.

37:04.933 --> 37:06.209
ADLON: Wow.

37:06.233 --> 37:07.642
GATES: Well,
guess what happened?

37:07.666 --> 37:11.276
When the German army reached
the village her mother-in-law

37:11.300 --> 37:14.476
gave her and the children up.

37:14.500 --> 37:18.876
ADLON: Oh, she told on them.

37:18.900 --> 37:21.876
She narked on their Jewishness.

37:21.900 --> 37:23.142
GATES: Yeah.

37:23.166 --> 37:26.642
ADLON: Wow. His mom?

37:26.666 --> 37:29.576
GATES: His mom.
She gave them up.

37:29.600 --> 37:31.933
ADLON: Why?

37:32.300 --> 37:34.009
GATES: The answer to
Pamela's question is part

37:34.033 --> 37:36.209
of a terrible history.

37:36.233 --> 37:40.742
The nazis, tapping into a
current of anti-Semitism as

37:40.766 --> 37:44.866
old as the middle ages, found
many willing collaborators.

37:45.733 --> 37:49.742
Simply put: the holocaust
was the culmination of

37:49.766 --> 37:52.166
centuries of hatred.

37:52.700 --> 37:55.842
Even so it's
appalling to contemplate.

37:55.866 --> 37:59.733
And Pamela was now
compelled to do so.

38:00.200 --> 38:04.176
According to a family friend,
Clara Birman and her children

38:04.200 --> 38:08.076
were among the roughly
33,000 Jewish people who were

38:08.100 --> 38:12.566
massacred in a large ravine
on the outskirts of Kiev,

38:13.200 --> 38:16.866
the capital city of Ukraine.

38:18.133 --> 38:20.809
Clara was 27 when
she was murdered.

38:20.833 --> 38:22.742
Her daughter was
three years old,

38:22.766 --> 38:25.242
her son one year old.

38:25.266 --> 38:28.576
Did you know that you had a
tangible family connection to

38:28.600 --> 38:29.709
the holocaust?

38:29.733 --> 38:34.666
ADLON: No. Not at all.
Not at all.

38:39.433 --> 38:44.409
And I was hoping that
they could still be alive.

38:44.433 --> 38:46.076
GATES: Yeah.

38:46.100 --> 38:47.442
ADLON: The babies.

38:47.466 --> 38:50.233
GATES: Yeah.

38:50.433 --> 38:52.433
(sighs)

38:52.733 --> 38:56.076
There is a small
grace note to this story,

38:56.100 --> 38:59.476
Clara's mother
Menikha survived the war,

38:59.500 --> 39:03.666
returned to Ukraine, and
was able to rebuild her life.

39:05.000 --> 39:11.400
She died in Kiev on may 6, 1969
at the age of 85,

39:12.133 --> 39:15.266
when Pamela was
about three years old.

39:16.766 --> 39:19.842
GATES: What's it like to learn
that you had family in Ukraine

39:19.866 --> 39:24.042
as recently as the 1960s?

39:24.066 --> 39:25.342
ADLON: That's nuts.

39:25.366 --> 39:26.609
GATES: Yeah.

39:26.633 --> 39:30.666
ADLON: That's nuts.
I mean I'm just, yeah.

39:33.433 --> 39:35.909
GATES: Your great-grandfather
Frank died right around the

39:35.933 --> 39:39.609
time of the German
invasion of soviet Ukraine.

39:39.633 --> 39:43.409
Frank's son, your grandfather
Harry died in Boston the same

39:43.433 --> 39:47.276
year as his aunt
Menikha died in Ukraine.

39:47.300 --> 39:48.376
ADLON: No.

39:48.400 --> 39:49.476
GATES: Yeah.

39:49.500 --> 39:50.909
ADLON: Harry died in 1969?

39:50.933 --> 39:52.376
GATES: Yeah. In Boston.

39:52.400 --> 39:55.209
ADLON: Oh, god.
He was a funny guy.

39:55.233 --> 39:57.076
GATES: Do you think your
grandfather knew that he

39:57.100 --> 40:00.800
had such close
relatives in Ukraine?

40:01.800 --> 40:03.709
ADLON: Maybe he did.

40:03.733 --> 40:04.976
GATES: I wonder.

40:05.000 --> 40:06.676
ADLON: I wonder. I don't...

40:06.700 --> 40:10.109
GATES: What's it like for
you to learn this part of

40:10.133 --> 40:13.266
your father's family story?

40:14.533 --> 40:18.133
ADLON: What's, what's so...

40:19.500 --> 40:23.800
Incredible to me is
how little families know

40:25.033 --> 40:31.066
about their stories and how
we just accept the crumbs and

40:32.333 --> 40:36.433
how, you know,

40:36.700 --> 40:39.033
we don't preserve our histories,

40:40.200 --> 40:45.233
you know, and how I think
people need to know this.

40:45.700 --> 40:50.309
Seeing all of these people,
that's what makes you realize

40:50.333 --> 40:52.542
that everybody is important.

40:52.566 --> 40:54.142
GATES: Right.

40:54.166 --> 40:55.642
ADLON: It's, it's...

40:55.666 --> 40:59.242
And how precious life is.

40:59.266 --> 41:02.709
It's just absolutely incredible.

41:02.733 --> 41:05.042
All of us are against all odds.

41:05.066 --> 41:07.176
GATES: Yes. All of us.

41:07.200 --> 41:09.309
Our survival has
been against all odds.

41:09.333 --> 41:11.366
ADLON: Yes. It's a miracle.

41:12.100 --> 41:15.166
GATES: We'd already explored
Kathryn Hahn's maternal roots,

41:15.900 --> 41:18.276
revealing how her third
great-grandfather came to

41:18.300 --> 41:22.300
America, leaving a wife
and six children behind.

41:23.600 --> 41:26.342
Now, turning to
Kathryn's father's ancestry,

41:26.366 --> 41:30.442
we had another story to tell,
with similar themes,

41:30.466 --> 41:33.066
but a much happier ending.

41:33.400 --> 41:35.742
It began with a ship that
arrived in New York from

41:35.766 --> 41:39.966
Ireland on December 9th, 1882.

41:40.233 --> 41:43.276
On board, was Kathryn's
great-great-grandmother,

41:43.300 --> 41:47.642
Mary O'Connell, traveling on
her own with six young children.

41:47.666 --> 41:50.900
Which raised a question:
where was their father?

41:51.733 --> 41:54.442
We knew his name,
John O'Connell, but

41:54.466 --> 41:58.676
we couldn't find him anywhere
on the passenger list.

41:58.700 --> 42:01.676
HAHN: And she,
there was no husband?

42:01.700 --> 42:03.176
GATES: That's right.
HAHN: Partner.

42:03.200 --> 42:04.609
GATES: So, the
husband's missing.

42:04.633 --> 42:07.009
Any idea why?
Just take a guess.

42:07.033 --> 42:07.977
HAHN: He died.

42:08.001 --> 42:09.709
GATES: That's a
good guess, but nope.

42:09.733 --> 42:11.276
And he didn't run away
with a 17-year-old...

42:11.300 --> 42:12.509
HAHN: Yeah, right.

42:12.533 --> 42:14.442
I was gonna say he's in
Wisconsin with a 17-year-old.

42:14.466 --> 42:15.509
GATES: Yeah.

42:15.533 --> 42:17.642
Yeah, at the same,
at the same bakery.

42:17.666 --> 42:18.809
HAHN: Right, exactly.

42:18.833 --> 42:20.009
GATES: No. Good story.

42:20.033 --> 42:22.309
He had emigrated to
the states around 1880,

42:22.333 --> 42:23.542
two years before.

42:23.566 --> 42:24.676
HAHN: Oh, to set up shop.

42:24.700 --> 42:25.776
GATES: Yeah.

42:25.800 --> 42:28.042
Likely to establish roots
and send money back home

42:28.066 --> 42:30.042
to pay for their passage.

42:30.066 --> 42:31.809
And that was common
among immigrant families.

42:31.833 --> 42:32.909
HAHN: Yes.

42:32.933 --> 42:34.542
GATES: And it must have
placed a great burden on

42:34.566 --> 42:35.776
both of them.

42:35.800 --> 42:37.409
But still, I think I'd
rather be John than Mary.

42:37.433 --> 42:38.542
HAHN: Yes.

42:38.566 --> 42:40.142
GATES: On a ship
with all those kids.

42:40.166 --> 42:42.066
HAHN: Wow.

42:42.666 --> 42:45.942
GATES: As it turns out, Mary's
husband wasn't the only member

42:45.966 --> 42:48.433
of her family waiting
for her in America.

42:49.266 --> 42:52.342
Her arrival marked the
close of a long and likely

42:52.366 --> 42:55.100
painful period in her life.

42:55.500 --> 42:57.676
Census records
revealed that Mary's parents,

42:57.700 --> 43:03.000
Patrick and Honora Daly, had
settled in Michigan in 1860.

43:04.266 --> 43:08.909
At the time, Mary would
have been about 13 years old.

43:08.933 --> 43:11.376
So you know what
this record means?

43:11.400 --> 43:14.076
It means that when your third
great-grandparents immigrated

43:14.100 --> 43:17.009
to the United States they
left their daughter Mary

43:17.033 --> 43:19.342
behind in Ireland.

43:19.366 --> 43:22.576
And we don't know why.
Likely it was economic.

43:22.600 --> 43:23.876
HAHN: Yes.

43:23.900 --> 43:25.276
GATES: They probably couldn't
afford to bring her so they

43:25.300 --> 43:26.476
had to make choices.

43:26.500 --> 43:27.909
HAHN: God.

43:27.933 --> 43:31.309
GATES: She likely stayed
with her grandparents back in

43:31.333 --> 43:34.509
Ireland, you know, waiting
for them to bring her over.

43:34.533 --> 43:35.609
HAHN: Yes.

43:35.633 --> 43:38.542
GATES: But that had
to be heart wrenching.

43:38.566 --> 43:40.276
HAHN: I've got a lot
of that in my family.

43:40.300 --> 43:41.409
GATES: Yup.

43:41.433 --> 43:43.566
HAHN: Separation.

43:44.166 --> 43:46.842
GATES: This story
was about to darken.

43:46.866 --> 43:50.676
Digging deeper, we realized
that Mary's parents emigrated

43:50.700 --> 43:56.309
much earlier than 1860, likely
when Mary was very young,

43:56.333 --> 43:58.833
around the year 1849.

43:59.500 --> 44:01.042
At the time,

44:01.066 --> 44:04.009
Ireland was in the midst of
the great potato famine,

44:04.033 --> 44:07.276
a cataclysm that claimed
the lives of roughly

44:07.300 --> 44:11.042
one million people, and drove
another two million to leave

44:11.066 --> 44:15.109
the country, meaning that
Mary grew up surrounded by

44:15.133 --> 44:17.809
a massive amount of suffering.

44:17.833 --> 44:23.066
Waiting, and likely praying
to join her parents in America.

44:24.533 --> 44:27.109
HAHN: Whew.
That sounds intense.

44:27.133 --> 44:28.242
GATES: Well, guess what?

44:28.266 --> 44:29.243
HAHN: What?

44:29.267 --> 44:31.942
GATES: She waited 30 years.

44:31.966 --> 44:36.566
She was separated from
her parents for 30 years.

44:37.766 --> 44:41.742
HAHN: Yeah.
Oh wow, okay.

44:41.766 --> 44:44.742
GATES: Patrick and
Honora even had a child,

44:44.766 --> 44:47.642
Mary's younger brother David,
while they were living here

44:47.666 --> 44:49.809
and she was living back there.

44:49.833 --> 44:52.776
HAHN: Hmm.

44:52.800 --> 44:55.342
GATES: It would be so long
David died before his sister

44:55.366 --> 44:58.842
Mary finally was able to
immigrate to the United States.

44:58.866 --> 45:00.742
HAHN: Unh-uh.

45:00.766 --> 45:02.909
GATES: They had
David, David dies.

45:02.933 --> 45:05.009
Imagine having a baby brother
on the other side of the

45:05.033 --> 45:08.609
Atlantic whom you
would never meet?

45:08.633 --> 45:13.733
HAHN: Mmm, I mean, it's
interesting to me because I'm

45:14.033 --> 45:18.276
having echoes of my maternal
side and the family that I...

45:18.300 --> 45:19.376
GATES: Oh yeah.

45:19.400 --> 45:20.842
HAHN: I just keep
seeing that ocean between...

45:20.866 --> 45:22.109
GATES: That's true.

45:22.133 --> 45:25.100
HAHN: Families.
That is really profound.

45:25.900 --> 45:29.942
GATES: Fortunately, the ocean
between Mary and her parents

45:29.966 --> 45:34.909
would close in 1882 when
finally Mary arrived in the

45:34.933 --> 45:38.833
United States, it's difficult
even to imagine what that

45:39.233 --> 45:43.166
reunion was like, or what
emotions remained unspoken.

45:43.966 --> 45:45.842
But we found an obituary,

45:45.866 --> 45:48.176
published almost 20 years later,

45:48.200 --> 45:50.976
which suggests that
separation didn't break

45:51.000 --> 45:53.100
the family's bonds.

45:53.866 --> 45:57.909
HAHN: "Mrs. Nora Daly died at
607 Pine Street last night,

45:57.933 --> 45:59.609
age 77 years.

45:59.633 --> 46:03.109
During the past two years
she's lived with her daughter,

46:03.133 --> 46:06.833
Mrs. Mary O'Connell,
at Lima, Ohio."

46:07.566 --> 46:10.276
GATES: Nora is,
of course Honora.

46:10.300 --> 46:13.209
And Honora, here listed as Nora,

46:13.233 --> 46:15.642
spent the last years of her
life living with the daughter

46:15.666 --> 46:20.500
she had left behind in
Ireland for over 30 years.

46:21.366 --> 46:25.700
HAHN: Oh my god.
Oh my god.

46:27.733 --> 46:30.409
So she raised,
without her parents,

46:30.433 --> 46:32.509
by herself, six children?

46:32.533 --> 46:33.876
GATES: Mmm-hmm.

46:33.900 --> 46:38.333
HAHN: And then came over
and took care of her mom.

46:38.766 --> 46:40.109
GATES: Mm-hmm.

46:40.133 --> 46:41.342
HAHN: In Lima, Ohio?

46:41.366 --> 46:42.542
GATES: That's right.

46:42.566 --> 46:45.100
HAHN: Hmm.

46:46.033 --> 46:48.076
"During the past few years she
has lived with her daughter,

46:48.100 --> 46:49.476
Mrs. Mary O'Connell, at Lima".

46:49.500 --> 46:51.176
Wow. Yeah.

46:51.200 --> 46:52.342
GATES: Yup.

46:52.366 --> 46:55.209
So do you think they were
making up for lost time?

46:55.233 --> 46:59.966
HAHN: Yeah, I mean, wow,
I'm just still, like...

47:00.666 --> 47:03.166
(gasps)

47:04.833 --> 47:08.109
GATES: We had one more
detail to share with Kathryn.

47:08.133 --> 47:11.042
As we combed through
the archives in Ireland,

47:11.066 --> 47:13.809
we came upon what's
called a "house book"

47:13.833 --> 47:16.542
for the year 1849.

47:16.566 --> 47:20.076
Conducted for tax purposes,
this book records the

47:20.100 --> 47:23.742
owners and conditions of
much of Ireland's property

47:23.766 --> 47:25.142
at the time.

47:25.166 --> 47:27.509
Its entries, for
the town land of Port,

47:27.533 --> 47:29.442
in County Limerick,

47:29.466 --> 47:33.700
allowed us to glimpse a
crucial part of Mary's story.

47:33.900 --> 47:36.209
HAHN: "Name and
description: David Connors.

47:36.233 --> 47:38.876
House: quality letter 3C."

47:38.900 --> 47:41.509
GATES: We believe that this is
the relative who took in your

47:41.533 --> 47:43.409
great-great-grandmother
Mary Daly,

47:43.433 --> 47:46.833
when her parents immigrated
to the United States.

47:47.666 --> 47:50.642
David would have been
Mary's maternal grandfather.

47:50.666 --> 47:54.166
HAHN: Oh.
Oh my god.

47:54.566 --> 47:56.776
GATES: And as you're guessing
from the picture you're

47:56.800 --> 47:59.309
looking at, you see that "3C"?

47:59.333 --> 48:03.009
That was a technical
term to describe the,

48:03.033 --> 48:05.976
uh, nature of the
dwelling in which they lived.

48:06.000 --> 48:08.242
It was a designation
used to rate buildings by

48:08.266 --> 48:09.776
age and materials.

48:09.800 --> 48:14.176
It means Patrick's house would
have had stone or mud walls

48:14.200 --> 48:15.942
with a thatched roof.

48:15.966 --> 48:18.342
And it was old
and out of repair.

48:18.366 --> 48:21.442
And on your left, you can see
an image of what these houses

48:21.466 --> 48:22.676
would have looked like.

48:22.700 --> 48:25.609
Can you imagine having to
live in a house like that?

48:25.633 --> 48:26.909
HAHN: No.

48:26.933 --> 48:30.842
GATES: And remember, 1849, the
year that house book record

48:30.866 --> 48:33.776
was taken was
smack dab in the middle

48:33.800 --> 48:35.642
of the great potato famine.

48:35.666 --> 48:38.033
So it would've been rough.

48:38.366 --> 48:40.876
Now, as Mary grew older, she
would've assumed a caregiving

48:40.900 --> 48:43.676
role for her grandparents
until she married your

48:43.700 --> 48:48.400
great-great-grandfather,
John O'Connell, in 1865.

48:49.333 --> 48:51.876
So, what's it been
like to learn her story?

48:51.900 --> 48:56.400
HAHN: I mean, this is, I,
I'd always known that the,

48:56.600 --> 48:59.542
that I was, you know, Irish,
but I had no idea that it,

48:59.566 --> 49:02.176
that there was a paper
trail that went this far.

49:02.200 --> 49:03.177
GATES: Mmm-hmm.

49:03.201 --> 49:04.809
HAHN: And there
is something very,

49:04.833 --> 49:08.242
um, moving to me
about, about seeing,

49:08.266 --> 49:10.709
these things and these people.

49:10.733 --> 49:15.566
Like, this is, this is,

49:15.833 --> 49:18.566
this is really crazy.

49:20.200 --> 49:23.509
GATES: The paper trail had now
run out for each of my guests.

49:23.533 --> 49:25.109
HAHN: Oh my god.

49:25.133 --> 49:28.333
GATES: It was time to
unfurl their family trees.

49:28.700 --> 49:31.709
Now filled with names
they'd never heard before.

49:31.733 --> 49:33.642
ADLON: So cool!

49:33.666 --> 49:35.842
GATES: What is it like to see
that you are descended from

49:35.866 --> 49:36.942
all these people?

49:36.966 --> 49:40.309
HAHN: It really is beautiful.
Just beautiful.

49:40.333 --> 49:42.442
GATES: And our
journey wasn't over.

49:42.466 --> 49:46.142
Turning to DNA, we were
able to add a few more very

49:46.166 --> 49:49.400
surprising names to
their newfound families.

49:50.233 --> 49:53.109
When we compared Pamela's
mother's DNA to that of

49:53.133 --> 49:55.709
other people who have
been in this series,

49:55.733 --> 49:57.976
we found a match,

49:58.000 --> 50:01.866
evidence of a relative that
Pamela didn't know she had.

50:03.166 --> 50:04.609
Close your eyes and make a wish.

50:04.633 --> 50:07.442
Of all the people you know,

50:07.466 --> 50:11.842
who would you, like,
die to be cousins with?

50:11.866 --> 50:14.600
ADLON: Redd Foxx.
Let's go.

50:18.333 --> 50:22.133
Shut up. What?

50:23.000 --> 50:24.642
GATES: That's right.

50:24.666 --> 50:27.942
You are cousins
with Meryl Streep.

50:27.966 --> 50:29.842
ADLON: Are you kidding me?

50:29.866 --> 50:34.476
What how.
I love her so much.

50:34.500 --> 50:38.933
Look. Juicing.
I love her.

50:40.700 --> 50:43.476
GATES: Meryl and Pamela's
mother share an identical

50:43.500 --> 50:46.642
segment of DNA on
their X chromosomes,

50:46.666 --> 50:50.500
meaning that they share a
common distant ancestor.

50:50.933 --> 50:53.309
So, it means if you had an
ideal family tree going back

50:53.333 --> 50:55.709
god knows how long
there would be somebody

50:55.733 --> 50:57.009
on both family trees.

50:57.033 --> 51:00.866
ADLON: This is unbelievable.
That's so cool.

51:02.533 --> 51:05.142
GATES: Kathryn, too,
has a DNA cousin,

51:05.166 --> 51:08.966
one whose identity would
expand her sense of her own.

51:13.233 --> 51:17.009
HAHN: What?
I am so excited!

51:17.033 --> 51:18.476
Wait, what is happening?

51:18.500 --> 51:20.976
GATES: Your mother shares an
identical stretch of DNA

51:21.000 --> 51:24.242
on her fourth chromosome
with actor and director

51:24.266 --> 51:25.742
Regina King.

51:25.766 --> 51:28.242
And since your mother
is related to Regina,

51:28.266 --> 51:30.776
that means you are
related to Regina, too.

51:30.800 --> 51:33.742
Regina is about, like an
average African American,

51:33.766 --> 51:37.676
Regina is 24% European.

51:37.700 --> 51:39.842
HAHN: I love it so much.
This is the best.

51:39.866 --> 51:41.242
I love it.

51:41.266 --> 51:44.076
GATES: And Regina is, her
European lines are descended

51:44.100 --> 51:47.509
almost exactly from the very
same places in Europe from

51:47.533 --> 51:48.842
which you descend.

51:48.866 --> 51:50.766
So that's how you're related.
How about that?

51:51.633 --> 51:53.442
HAHN: Oh my god.
That makes me so happy.

51:53.466 --> 51:56.266
I, I, that is incredible.

51:56.466 --> 51:58.842
GATES: That's the end of our
journey with Kathryn Hahn

51:58.866 --> 52:00.776
and Pamela Adlon.

52:00.800 --> 52:04.176
Join me next time when we
unlock the secrets of the past

52:04.200 --> 52:05.609
for new guests,

52:05.633 --> 52:09.333
on another episode of
"Finding Your Roots."
